<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-966-668  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 966 668.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Dec 11 1989 v8 n25 p46(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Protocols lag behind fiber-optic media, experts say.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Olsen, Florence.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsProtocolFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardCommunications TechnologyComparisonNetwork Control ProcessorsPerformance.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Protocols Lag Behind Fiber-Optic Media, Experts SayandM;Federal network strategists who think they will get 10 times better networkperformance by moving up from 10-megabit/sec Ethernet to a 100-megabit/secfiber-optic network likely will be disappointed.andM;Today's widely used communications protocols are no match for the newhigh-speed media such as the Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI), severalfiber experts said at the recent Network Roundtable in Washington.andM;The Government Open Systems Interconnection Profile (GOSIP) is not ahigh-performance communications standard, said Ed Hotard, a senior systemsengineer with Martin Marietta Corp.andM;&quot;The GOSIP suite right now is not optimized for performance,&quot; he said.andO;&quot;GOSIP, and also all of OSI [the Open Systems Interconnection standardsmodel], was really optimized for functionality.&quot;andM;Another engineer, speaking at the roundtable sponsored by the Association forComputing Machinery, said, &quot;OSI, TCP/IP, XNS and SNA -- all the protoclstacks today -- are bottlenecks that in the past haven't been bothersome.&quot;andM;Mark Hoover, a systems engineering supervisor of high-speed data networkproducts for ATandamp;T Data Systems Group in Morristown, N.J., said, &quot;that'sbecause the hardware they were running on couldn't feed them data fast enoughanyway.&quot;andM;With FDDI, the bottlenecks occur when people try to push data from theirapplication through the networking protocol stack to the data link interface,Hoover said.andM;&quot;As long as that's the limitation, it doesn't matter how fast that the datalink interface is, I'm going to the same performance,&quot; he said.andM;High-speed, fiber-optic media simply can move data faster than the networkcontroller and protocol software can handle it, Hotard added.andM;&quot;What we need are protocols capable of keeping up with the media,&quot; he said.andM;Some people in the industry believe that with modifications, TCP/IP couldmeet the higher bandwidth requirements, Hoover said.andP;  Another candidate mightbe the Express Transfer Protocol, or XTP, but it has not been recognized byany standards group, he said.andM;Hoover said people usually have two reasons for wanting a high-speed FDDIdata link.andP;  It can be a backbone, or concentration point, for lower-speedlocal area networks.andM;&quot;But people also are going to want to connect their servers up to thathigh-speed data link to get greater performance and communications betweentwo end points.&quot; Hoover said.andM;And they would not get it, he said.andM;More work is needed before general-purpose protocol stacks, such as GOSIP,can offer the government the values of low cost, high performance andmultivendor interoperability, he said.andM;Everyone wokring in high-speed data networking today is looking at fasterprotocols and devising their own, Hoover said.andM;&quot;What's needed now is for the vendor community to rally behind one or two orthree of these proposals, flesh them out and get them from the research levelto the product level,&quot; he said.andM;The faster protocols will be developed, Hoover predicted.andP;  And he also saidfiber is a safe bet as a network media, despite the high cost today of fivervs.andP;  copper wire.andM;&quot;By 1990, the gap will be pretty small,&quot; Hoover said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>